The Johns Hopkins Novel Corona Virus (COVID-19) epidemiological data is compiled by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CCSE) from various sources.
The dataset contains data since 22nd of January 2020. For the data and more information about it, please visit here.

Q1

Data Preparation and Manipulation

(25 points)

  1. We first prepare and aggregate the data.
  1. First, load the Corona Confirmed Cases Narrow, the Corona Confirmed Deaths Narrow, and the Corona Confirmed Recovered Narrow datasets directly from the Johns Hopkins website.
    The type of the Date variable should be date type. (2 pts)
  2. Create new data-frames named cases.agg, deaths.agg, and recovered.agg which aggregate the sum of Corona cases, deaths, and recovered respectively over the different countries provinces. To do this, aggregate Value using only the country and date features, ignoring all other features (similarly to what has been shown in lecture 2).
    To achieve the aggregation use the aggregate function. In addition, order the data-frame first by Country and then by Date (increasing order). The columns of each of the two resulting data-frames should be Country.Region, Date, Value. (5pts)
  3. Repeat (b) using tidyverse and the pipe. Show that the outputs from the two methods are the same. (5pts)
  4. Using the last day of March as a reference, create a single stacked bar-plot that visualizes the top 10 countries in terms of their Corona cases, and their respected Corona deaths and recovered cases stacked on top of the current sick people in three different colors (each stack should add up to total cases). Make sure that the first stack shows the number of confirmed Corona sick people (sick = cases - deaths - recovered). Each stacked bar should represent a country. Please use the barplot base R function to create this plot. I recommend everyone to read the help documentation for barplot ; go over the expected input, and the different parameters. What is the biggest issue with the information presented in this plot? (13pts)

Solution:

# loading the data frames:
confirmed <- read.csv(file = url_cases, header = T, comment.char = "#")
recovered <- read.csv(file= url_recovered, header = T, comment.char = "#")
deaths <- read.csv(file= url_deaths, header = T, comment.char = "#")

#(a)- Date type for the date culomns:
confirmed$Date <- as.Date(confirmed$Date)
deaths$Date <- as.Date(deaths$Date)
recovered$Date <- as.Date(recovered$Date)

msg <- "The type of the Date column in table"
dataframes_names <- c("confirmed", "recovered", "deaths")
dataframes <- c(confirmed, recovered, deaths)
for(i in 1:3)
{
  cat(msg, dataframes_names[i], "is:", class(dataframes[[5+ 10*(i-1)]]), "\n")
  }
## The type of the Date column in table confirmed is: Date 
## The type of the Date column in table recovered is: Date 
## The type of the Date column in table deaths is: Date
#(b) - ordering the aggregated tables by date and country
cases.agg <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = confirmed, FUN = sum)
deaths.agg <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = deaths, FUN = sum)
recovered.agg <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = recovered, FUN = sum)

# ordering each aggregated table by country and date:
cases.agg <- cases.agg[order(cases.agg$Date),]
cases.agg <- cases.agg[order(cases.agg$Country.Region),]

recovered.agg <- recovered.agg[order(recovered.agg$Date),]
recovered.agg <- recovered.agg[order(recovered.agg$Country.Region),]

deaths.agg <- deaths.agg[order(deaths.agg$Date),]
deaths.agg <- deaths.agg[order(deaths.agg$Country.Region),]

#(c) - ordering using dplyr (tidyverse) and pipe, showing same results
library("dplyr")

# we make copies of the unorginized aggregated tables:
cases.agg_copy <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = confirmed, FUN = sum)
deaths.agg_copy <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = deaths, FUN = sum)
recovered.agg_copy <- aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region + Date, data = recovered, FUN = sum)

# we orginize with the pipe and tidyverse:
cases.agg_tidy <- cases.agg_copy %>% arrange(Country.Region, Date)
deaths.agg_tidy <- deaths.agg_copy %>% arrange(Country.Region, Date)
recovered.agg_tidy <- recovered.agg_copy %>% arrange(Country.Region, Date)
## Equality between the ordered confirmed cases, ordered with and without the pipe: TRUE
## 
## Equality between the ordered deaths cases, ordered with and without the pipe: TRUE
## 
## Equality between the ordered recovered cases, ordered with and without the pipe: TRUE
#(d) -  plotting a single stacked bar-plot:

# we filter each table by last day of March:
cases_end_march <- filter(.data = cases.agg, Date == "2020-03-31")
deaths_end_march <- filter(.data = deaths.agg, Date == "2020-03-31")
recovered_end_march <- filter(.data = recovered.agg, Date == "2020-03-31")

# we add to the original table we work on verctors of deaths and recovered on March 31st:
cases_end_march$Deaths <- deaths_end_march$Value
cases_end_march$Recovered <- recovered_end_march$Value
# we slice only the last 10 countries with the highest number of CONFIRMED CASES:
cases_end_march <- arrange(.data = cases_end_march, desc(Value))[c(1:10),]

# memory cleaning...
rm(deaths_end_march)
rm(recovered_end_march)
rm(cases.agg_copy)
rm(recovered.agg_copy)
rm(deaths.agg_copy)

# create a sick column:
cases_end_march$Sick <- (cases_end_march$Value)-(cases_end_march$Deaths)-(cases_end_march$Recovered)

# creating the stacked-bars plot:
 
# creating a matrix of numbers to pile up as stacked bars:
numbers_matrix <- as.matrix(data.frame(cases_end_march$Sick,cases_end_march$Recovered, cases_end_march$Deaths))
# plotting:
title_main <- "Distribution of cases in the 10 most confirmed countries"

subtitle <- "Confirmed sick, recovered and dead on the last day of March"

colors_for_plot <- c("skyblue1", "dodgerblue1", "mediumblue") 

# we write the countries manualy so that UK could have 2 lines:
countries <- c("US", "Italy", "Span", "China", "Germany", 
               "France", "Iran","United \nKingdom", "Swizerland", "Turkey")

stacked_plot<- barplot(height = t(numbers_matrix), names.arg = countries, 
                       las = 2,  ylim = c(0 , 200000), main = title_main,
                       beside = F, col= colors_for_plot,  font = 2,
                       cex.names = 0.85, legend.text = c("Sick", "Recovered", "Dead"))

text(x = stacked_plot, y= cases_end_march$Value + 9000, cex = 0.9, xpd= T, 
     label = cases_end_march$Value, font = 2)

The biggest issue with the information presented in this plot, in our opinion:

We think that the biggest issue with the information presented in this plot, is that China seems to have a fewer number of cases than the US, and seems to report a large number of recovered civilians. We find it hard to believe the numbers, and to accept that most of the people in China have recovered, compared to what we can see in the news.



Q2

Analysis of Daily New Corona Cases and Deaths

20 points

The two datasets (Corona Cases and Deaths) register the value of cases and deaths, respectively, as a cumulative sum for each day. In this question we would like to understand the daily differences between consecutive days.

  1. Add a new column named Diff to both the cases.agg and the deaths.agg data-frames. This new column should register the daily Value difference for each country. In other words, the Diff column shows how many new cases/deaths each country incurs every day. Hint - diff must be per country. (7pts)
  2. Find the top 10 instances of country and date combinations with the greatest absolute number of new daily Corona cases and deaths (separately). Print the result in a descriptive format. (5pts)
  3. In one figure, plot Italys new daily Corona cases AND deaths as a function of Date. Choose the plot type you think that makes the most sense. (3pts)
  4. Plot the same graph as in (c), but this time plot the number of new cases on the logarithm scale. What can we learn? (5pts)

Solution:

#(a) inserting a difference vector to the cases and deaths aggregated tables:

# we first add zeros, so everytime we switch a country, the difference shall start again from zero.
# some countries do not start with zero cases, but we cannot decide how many added in the last day.

cases.agg$Diff <- 0
deaths.agg$Diff <- 0

for(i in 1 : (length(cases.agg$Value)-1) )
{
  ifelse(test = (cases.agg$Country.Region[i] == cases.agg$Country.Region[i+1]) ,
         cases.agg$Diff[i+1] <- (cases.agg$Value[i+1]-cases.agg$Value[i]),
         cases.agg$Diff[i+1] <- cases.agg$Diff[i+1])
  
   ifelse(test = (deaths.agg$Country.Region[i] == deaths.agg$Country.Region[i+1]) ,
         deaths.agg$Diff[i+1] <- (deaths.agg$Value[i+1]-deaths.agg$Value[i]),
         deaths.agg$Diff[i+1] <- deaths.agg$Diff[i+1])
}

#(b) 10 combination of country and date, for which the daily increase was highest:
cases.agg_copy <- dplyr::select(.data = cases.agg, colnames(cases.agg))
deaths.agg_copy <- dplyr::select(.data = deaths.agg, colnames(deaths.agg))

cases.agg_copy <- arrange(.data = cases.agg_copy, desc(Diff))
cases.agg_copy <- dplyr::select(.data = cases.agg_copy,Country.Region, Date, Diff)[1:10 ,]

deaths.agg_copy <-arrange(.data = deaths.agg_copy, desc(Diff)) 
deaths.agg_copy <- dplyr::select(.data = deaths.agg_copy, Country.Region, Date, Diff)[1:10 ,]

#creating the relevant data for our plot:
increase_cases <- cases.agg %>% filter(Country.Region == "Italy") %>% select(Date, Diff)
increase_cases$index <- as.factor(floor(((increase_cases$Date)-as.Date("2020-01-22"))/7))
height_cases <- aggregate(Diff ~ index, data = increase_cases, FUN = sum)[1:12,]

increase_deaths <- deaths.agg %>% filter(Country.Region == "Italy") %>% select(Date, Diff)
increase_deaths$index <- as.factor(floor(((increase_deaths$Date)-as.Date("2020-01-22"))/7))
height_deaths <- aggregate(Diff ~ index, data = increase_deaths, FUN = sum)[1:12,]

bp <- barplot(height = height_cases$Dif, ylim = c(0, 50000), xlim = c(0, 14) ,
              col = "paleturquoise2", 
              main = "Sum of Italy's weekly increase in confirmed cases and deaths",
              xlab = "Full weeks since Jenuary 22",
              names.arg = height_cases$index,legend = T)

barplot(height_deaths$Diff, add  = T, col = "salmon", legend= T)

weeks_legend <- c("Week 0: 22/1 - 28/1","Week 1: 29/1 - 4/2", "Week 2: 5/2 - 11/2",
                  "Week 3: 12/2 - 18/2", "Week 4: 19/2 - 25/2", "Week 5: 26/2 - 3/3"
                  ,"Week 6: 4/3 - 10/3","Week 7: 11/3 - 17/3","Week 8: 18/3 - 24/3",
                  "Week 9: 25/3 - 31/3","Week 10: 1/4 - 7/4", "Week 11: 8/4 - 14/4")

legend(x = 13 ,y = 52000, legend = c("Cases", "Deaths"), fill = c("paleturquoise2", "salmon"), bty = "n",
       y.intersp = 1.5, xpd = T)

legend(x = -0.8, y = 51000, legend = weeks_legend ,bty  = 'n', 
       y.intersp = 1.2, xpd = T, cex = 0.8)

text(x= bp,y=  height_cases$Diff + 6500, labels = height_cases$Diff, xpd = T, font = 2, cex = 0.8)
text(x= bp,y=  height_deaths$Diff + 3600, labels = height_deaths$Diff, xpd = T, font = 2,cex = 0.8)

#(d) - logrithmic scale for the last graph:

# creating the log vectors:
log_cases <- log(height_cases$Dif)
log_deaths <- log(height_deaths$Diff)
for(i in 1: length(log_cases))
{
  ifelse(log_cases[i] == -Inf, log_cases[i]<- 0, log_cases[i]<-log_cases[i])
  ifelse(log_deaths[i] == -Inf, log_deaths[i]<- 0, log_deaths[i]<-log_deaths[i])
}
bp_log <- barplot(height = log_cases , ylim = c(0, 15),
              col = "paleturquoise2", 
              main = "Logarithmic scale for weekly increase in cases/deaths in Italy",
              xlab = "Full weeks since Jenuary 22",
              names.arg = height_cases$index,legend = T)

barplot(log_deaths, add  = T, col = "salmon", legend= T)

weeks_legend <- c("Week 0: 22/1 - 28/1","Week 1: 29/1 - 4/2", "Week 2: 5/2 - 11/2",
                  "Week 3: 12/2 - 18/2", "Week 4: 19/2 - 25/2", "Week 5: 26/2 - 3/3"
                  ,"Week 6: 4/3 - 10/3","Week 7: 11/3 - 17/3","Week 8: 18/3 - 24/3",
                  "Week 9: 25/3 - 31/3","Week 10: 1/4 - 7/4", "Week 11: 8/4 - 14/4")

legend(x = 12 ,y = 15, legend = c("Cases", "Deaths"), fill = c("paleturquoise2", "salmon"), bty = "n",
       y.intersp = 1.2, xpd = T)

legend(x = -0.8, y = 14.6, legend = weeks_legend ,bty  = 'n', 
       y.intersp = 1.2, xpd = T, cex = 0.8)

text(x= bp_log, y=  log_cases + 0.7 , labels = round(log_cases, 2) , xpd = T, font = 2, cex = 0.8)
text(x= bp_log, y=  log_deaths + 0.7, labels = round(log_deaths,2) , xpd = T, font = 2,cex = 0.8)

What can we learn from applying log on the weekly increase scale:

We think that the logarithmic scale can distinguish weeks in which there was a linear growth scale or exponential growth scale. Since \(\ln({e^{cx}}) = cx\) the linear growth part is respective to an exponential growth, and the part where we can spot quite moderate (to almost none) changes, we can assume to look at linear growth, since \(\ln(C) = C'\) for \(C, C' \in \mathbb{R}\)

Preparing and Analyzing the World Bank Data

25 points

  1. Rename the columns of eco_data: country,S_country,feature,feature_code,Y2018V,Y2019V. (2pts)
  2. Create a new eco data-frame whose dimensions are \(N \times 11\), where N is the number of countries. The first column should include the names of the countries in eco_data.
    The rest of the columns should be the features with their respective values in eco_data for each country from 2018. Print the head of the new data-frame.(8pts).
    In other words, in this question you are asked to create a new eco data-frame whose dimensions are \(N \times 11\), where N is the number of countries (the first column should include the names of the countries in eco_data). The rest of the columns should be the features with their respective values in eco_data for each country from 2018. Print the head of the new data-frame. You may delete rows with NA as a country value only.
  3. Select and rename the following columns: country as country, GDP(US currency) as GDP, Population ages 65 and above (% of total population) as pop65, Population in the largest city (% of urban population) as pop_city_ratio, Population, total as pop_total columns . (2pts)
  4. Show a table of the five countries with the highest per capita GDP in 2018.
    Next (considering all countries), plot the % of population over 65 vs.log of GDP per capita in 2018, after excluding the 10% countries with the lowest GDP per capita. Using lm and abline, add a regression line to the plot. What is your conclusion? (13 pts)

#loading the `eco_data`:
eco_data <- read.csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DataScienceHU/DataAnalysisR_2020/master/data/economic_data.csv"))
#(a) - renaming the table's columns names:
colnames(x = eco_data) <- c("country", "S_country", "feature","feature_code","Y2018V","Y2019V")

#(b) - creating the new data frame:

# creating the data frame:
eco <- as.data.frame(matrix(nrow = 264, ncol = 11))

#naming the columns:
colnames(eco)<- append(c("country"),as.character(eco_data$feature[1:10]))

#extracting data from the original data frame:
eco$country <- as.character(unique(eco_data$country)[1:264])
for(i in 2:11)
{
  eco[,i] <- eco_data$Y2018V[eco_data$feature ==  colnames(eco)[i]]
}

# replacing ".." marks with NA:
for(i in 1:264)
  {
  for(j in 1:11)
    {
    ifelse(as.character(eco[i,j]) == "..", eco[i,j]<- NA, eco[i,j]<-eco[i,j])
    }
}

print(head(eco))

Q4

Joining the Datasets

20 points

  1. Join the deaths.agg, cases.agg, and recovered.agg into one data-frame called corona.(5pts)
  2. Join the corona and eco data-frames in a way that will keep the most information regarding the data (but not full join).
    Make sure that no essential data is thrown away (show this). (3pts)
  3. Create new columns of normalized cases, deaths, and recovered so they will show the number of cases per 100,000 people for each country.
    Using the last day of March as a reference, create a single stacked bar plot that visualizes the top 10 countries in terms of normalized Corona cases, and their respected normalized Corona deaths and recovered, as done in Q1.
    how is it different from the graph before normalization? (5pts)
  4. Using the last day of March as a reference, create a scatter-plot of normalized deaths and cases vs.pop65. Limit the plot to show only countries with 15% or more of pop65.
    In addition, color the outliers( pop65>24, norm100K_deaths>15) in that plot in red and add to the plot their country names (7pts)

Solution:

#(a) - joining tables, and creating 'corona':

corona <- select(.data = cases.agg, "country" = Country.Region, Date, "Value (cases)" = Value, "Diff (cases)" = Diff)
corona <- mutate(.data = corona, "Value (deaths)" = deaths.agg$Value,"Diff (deaths)" = deaths.agg$Diff,
                 "Value (recovered)" = recovered.agg$Value)
corona$country <- as.character(corona$country)

#(b) - merging corona and eco, while losing as least information as possible from the data:

# eco is the biggest table, and it contains the countries of corona, plus some rows, regarding islands \ and economical issues (not countries)
# Therefore, we'd cut out anything that is not a proper country, while correcting names of the same places that dont match.

eco$country <- as.character(eco$country)
eco <- eco[1:216,]
# many countries were in both tables but didn't share the exact name. we'll make sure we have a mtching name, so we can join the tables according to the intersecting countries:

countries_to_fix <- c("Bahamas", "Brunei", "Congo (Brazzaville)", "Congo (Kinshasa)", "Czechia", "Egypt","Gambia", 
                      "Iran", "Korea, South","Kyrgyzstan","Laos", "Russia","Slovakia", "Saint Kitts and Nevis",
                      "Saint Lucia","Saint Vincent and the Grenadines", "Syria", "US", "Venezuela", "Yemen")

indices_to_fix <- c(14, 29, 45, 46, 53, 59, 72, 92, 105,108,109,162,174,182,183,185,190, 207, 211,215)

for(i in 1:length(countries_to_fix))
{
  eco$country[indices_to_fix[i]] <- countries_to_fix[i]
}

#(a) - (1) creating the joint table:
corona_eco_joint <- inner_join(x = corona, y= eco, by= "country")

# we correct the names of the columns as we did in the last question:
names_to_correct <- c("GDP","pop65", "pop_city_ratio", "pop_total")
indices_to_fix_names <- c(8, 17, 15, 14)

for(i in 1:4)
  {
  colnames(corona_eco_joint)[indices_to_fix_names[i]] <- names_to_correct[i]
}

corona_eco_joint$pop_total <- as.numeric(as.character(corona_eco_joint$pop_total))

#(b) - 
# (1) - creating normalized columns per 100k people:
corona_eco_joint$"Sick" <- corona_eco_joint$`Value (cases)` - corona_eco_joint$`Value (deaths)` - corona_eco_joint$`Value (recovered)`
corona_eco_joint$"Cases normalized" <-  100000*((corona_eco_joint$`Value (cases)`)/(corona_eco_joint$pop_total))
corona_eco_joint$"Deaths normalized" <- 100000*((corona_eco_joint$`Value (deaths)`)/(corona_eco_joint$pop_total))
corona_eco_joint$"Recovered normalized" <- 100000*((corona_eco_joint$`Value (recovered)`)/(corona_eco_joint$pop_total))
corona_eco_joint$"Sick normalized" <- 100000*((corona_eco_joint$Sick )/(corona_eco_joint$pop_total)) 

# (2) - single stacked bar plot for the 10 countries highest in normalized cases at the end of march:

joint_end_march <- corona_eco_joint %>% filter(Date == "2020-03-31")
joint_end_march <- arrange(.data = joint_end_march, desc(`Cases normalized`))[1:10,]

# in order to make a stacked barplot we have to create a transposed matrix again:

normalized_matrix <- t(as.matrix(data.frame(joint_end_march$`Sick normalized`,
                                          joint_end_march$`Recovered normalized`,
                                          joint_end_march$`Deaths normalized`)))
#cosmetic changes:
country_names <- joint_end_march$country
colors_normalized <- c("mediumpurple1", "purple3", "purple4")

#the graph:
stack_plot <- barplot(height = normalized_matrix, beside = F, names.arg = country_names,
                      cex.names = 0.75, las = 2, ylim = c(0, 800),
                      cex.axis = 0.8, main = "Top 10 countries with sick, dead and recovered per 100K people",
                      ylab = "Number per 100K", legend.text = c("Sick", "Recovered", "Dead"),
                      col = colors_normalized, font = 2)

text(x = stack_plot, y= joint_end_march$`Cases normalized` + 40, cex = 0.9, xpd= T, 
     label = round(joint_end_march$`Cases normalized`, 1), font = 2)

4.c: Difference between a normalized graph and a normal one:

As opposed to the original cases values, the normalized cases per 100k helps distinguish the relative quantity per capita in each coutry. If we didnt normalize the cases, wed probably get a list of the biggest and most crowded countries, like US or China (we checked, and we did). normalizing the nimber of cases per 100k help see how hard each country was affected, relative to its own scale. Relatively to their rather small population, we can observe that places like San marino or Iceland are highly affected by the corona, but that knowledge could be easily missed if we dont normalize.

Q5

Open Question

10 points

Write an interesting research question regarding the Corona outbreak and then follow the steps to answer it using tables and plots. You can use the loaded datasets or any other dataset you find as long as you add the data file to your lab1 repository so it can be loaded directly from a url (e.g.the World Bank). This question will be graded based on creativity, originality, and the novelty of the analysis.

Solution:

Research question: Do infrastructures (Electricity, phone, health system) are factors of dealing with the corona outbreak? How big is their influence?

Hypothesis: We assume that having good based infrastructures can improve the way a country can deal with a pandemic outbreak:

  • Phones: contribute to data spreading and communicating.
  • Electricity: contributes to working from home, and staying home, while minimizing the need to go outside.
  • Health system: assuming corona virus will every country eventually, wed like to assume that a well-prepared health system will deal better with the outbreak.

Well look at the first day of March as a reference, assuming that day is somehow balanced between outbreak and knowledge about the virus, which means, we believe that a country with good infrastructures (as mentioned before) might get a better information in advance and/or have a more prepared health system in the country, thus getting less affected at this point of time.

Data analysis:

# Necessary datasets:
phone <- read.csv("telephone.csv", header = T)
electricity <- read.csv("elec.csv", header = T)
health <- read.csv("health.csv", header = T)

# filtering 2017 only: 
phone <- phone[,c(1,7)]
health <- health[,c(1,5)]
electricity <- electricity[,c(1, 6)]

#changing names:
colnames(phone) <- c("country", "phones per capita")
colnames(health) <- c("country", "health")
colnames(electricity) <- c("country", "electricity")

phone$`phones per capita` <- phone$`phones per capita` / 100
infrastructures <- inner_join(x = inner_join(x = phone, y = health, by = "country"), y = electricity, by="country")
infrastructures <- infrastructures %>% arrange(country)

# name correction to the countries again:

names_indices <- c(15, 30, 48,49,56,66,85,112,125,128,129,201,213,224,225,227,235,252,257,262)
new_names <- countries_to_fix
infrastructures$country <- as.character(infrastructures$country)

for (i in 1:length(names_indices)) 
{
  infrastructures$country[names_indices[i]] <- new_names[i]
}

# we'll filter the 15 countries with the most cases at the first day of march (China excluded),
# since the corona virus is originated in china, it's not relevant to our research question:

march_first <- corona %>% filter(Date == "2020-03-01")
